<H1> Seneca: Suasoriae</H1> 
<BR>

<P> <I><P> <I>The 'Suasoriae' and 'Controversiae' of <A HREf="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Seneca_the_Elder">Seneca the Elder</A> are the main source of information about the practice of <A HREF="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Declamation#History">Declamation</A> in the early Roman empire. In his old age, probably not long before 40 A.D., Seneca wrote his reminiscences of declamations that he had heard during the reigns of Augustus and Tiberius. <A HREF="../translate/suasoria6.html">Suasoria 6</A> also contains some useful excerpts from other writers, describing the character and death of Cicero.</I>
 
<P> <I>This English translation of the Suasoriae is by W.A. Edward (Cambridge, 1928). The Latin text, as edited by A.G. Kiessling (Teubner, 1872), can be found in <A HREF="https://anastrophe.uchicago.edu/cgi-bin/perseus/citequery3.pl?dbname=LatinAugust21&getid=0&query=Sen.%20Suas.%201">Perseus under Philologic</A>. </I></P><BR>

